<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-717-654  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 717 654.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 23 1990 v7 n30 p26(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Panic at the helm: the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals may haveplaced regulators in uncharted, dangerous waters. (FederalCommunications Commission's Third Computer Inquiry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pearce, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In Jun 1990 the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals in San Franciscoreversed the Federal Communications Commission's (FCC's) ComputerIII decision.andP;  Unless the ruling is modified, the decision willnegate the FCC's Computer III orders and increase the regulatoryauthority of state public utility commissions to control enhancedand information services.andP;  The FCC used Computer III to developthe Open Network Architecture (ONA) regulation and combined itwith accounting and cost allocation rules to keep telephonecompanies from subsidizing information services with revenue fromother services.andP;  The Circuit Court decided that the FCC hadexceeded its authority and was acting contrary to theAdministrative Procedure Act.andP;  Subsequent postponement of theimplementation of ONA will mean restricted user choice.andP;  The FCC'smajor setback was on the preemption of state regulation ofinformation services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Circuit courtsUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionProposalOpen Network ArchitectureCourt CasesInformation ServicesBell Regional Holding CompaniesCommunications Service SuppliersTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>